1.2 QQ against a normal distribution

# z transform expression (mean = 0, variance = 1)
expr1_5 <- expr1_5 %>% mutate(scaled.exp = (expr1_5$TCGA.BH.A0C7.01 - mean(expr1_5$TCGA.BH.A0C7.01)) / sd(expr1_5$TCGA.BH.A0C7.01))

# check
head(expr1_5)
##      sample TCGA.BH.A0C7.01 scaled.exp
## 1 ARHGEF10L         10.0931  0.5360552
## 2     RNF10         11.3820  1.2070090
## 3     RNF11         10.7663  0.8864983
## 4     RNF13         10.3366  0.6628123
## 5   GTF2IP1         12.7240  1.9056047
## 6   RTN4RL2          5.0910 -2.0678534
mean(expr1_5$scaled.exp) # pretty much 0, good
## [1] -2.132467e-16
mean(var(expr1_5$scaled.exp)) # 1, good
## [1] 1
# qqplot with normal distribution
qqnorm(expr1_5$scaled.exp)
qqline(expr1_5$scaled.exp)

1.2 Explanation

The data looks like it follows a normal distribution pretty well according to the qqplot. It might be slightly right skewed based on how the higher data points come off of the qqnorm line around x=3. It also looks like it might have a fat lower tail since the lower data points plateau around x=-2.

1.3 KS Test against normal

# KS test of z transformed data against normal distribution
ks.test(expr1_5$scaled.exp, pnorm)
## Warning in ks.test(expr1_5$scaled.exp, pnorm): ties should not be present for
## the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  expr1_5$scaled.exp
## D = 0.020398, p-value = 2.58e-05
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

1.3 Explanation

The KS test comparing our filtered and transformed data to a normal distribution gave a p-value of 2.58e-5 and a test statistic, D, of 0.02. The results of the KS test were significant indicating that it is likely our data was sampled from a population that does not follow a normal distribution for these expression levels.

2.2 Feature A vs Feature B

# scatterplot of A vs B
AvB <- ggplot(fake4, aes(x=featB, y=featA)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Feature A vs. Feature B",
       x = "Feature B",
       y = "Feature A") +
  geom_path(aes(color = time), size = 1.5, alpha = 0.7) +
  theme_minimal()

AvB

2.3 Explanation of feature A and feature B

As time progresses, feature A appears to cyclically increase pretty steadily according to scatter_a. Conversely, feature B appears to cyclically decrease at a slower rate than feature A increases, according to scatter_b. Additionally, there appears to be one point in feature B at time = 40 that does not follow the rest of the pattern. Looking at plot AvB, we can see that feature B starts around 100 while feature A starts around 45. The color of the line indicates time progressing, where the line becomes lighter as time moves forward. The two features appear to move in the same direction periodically, around time points 0-2, 6-11, 18-25, and 38-46.

3.2 Optimal sliding window parameters

# optimal phast plot
phast_4 <- data.frame(rollmean(phast,200, fill = NA))
phast_4_plot <- ggplot(phast_4, aes(x=bp, y=metric_1)) +
  geom_point(color = "aquamarine3", size = 1, alpha = 0.2) +
  labs( title = "Metric 1 vs. basepair position for Phast data, k = 200",
        x = "Basepair Position",
        y = "Metric 1") +
  theme_minimal()

phast_4_plot
## Warning: Removed 199 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# optimal phylo plot
phylo_4 <- data.frame(rollmean(phylo, 200, fill = NA))

phylo_4_plot <- ggplot(phylo_4, aes(x=bp, y=metric_2)) +
  geom_point(color = "deeppink", size = 1, alpha = 0.2) +
  labs( title = "Metric 2 vs. basepair position for Phylo data, k = 200",
        x = "Basepair Position",
        y = "Metric 2") +
  theme_minimal()

phylo_4_plot
## Warning: Removed 199 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

3.2 Explanations

After adjusting parameters for both the phast and phylo data, k=200 seems to give a decent picture of the data for both metrics. When adjusting k to less than 100, the graphs become too granular and it is difficult to distinguish actual peaks from noise. When the k is set too high, it oversimplifies any underlying trends in the data that may be important.

4.6 Interpretation of histogram

The loop runs a chi square test on a random sampling of genes to see if the observed proportion of TSG or OG genes in our random sample is similar to the expected proportion. A significant p value (p<0.05) tells us that any observed deviation is due to more than just chance. There are 74 p values generated from our loop that are significant while 926 are not. Our histogram of p values is weakly bimodal and there are p values all the way from 0.0 to 1.0.

Question 5

5.1 Hierarchical cluster plot

Hierarchical cluster plots use a dendrogram format but create a circle where the outside groupings can be labeled and designated using different clusters. These plots, like dendrograms, use nodes and edges to represent multiple dimensions in a dataset.

5.2 Dendrogram

Dendrograms use nodes and edges to represent dimensions. Nodes are where the data splits into more categories (can be parent, intermediate, or terminal node) and edges represent the relationship. The distance between two points can also be calculated using dendrograms.

5.3 K-means clustering

K-means clustering allows you to see how datapoints cluster based on their means. This is similar to PCA for ancestry. You can calculate the distance metric (multiple ways to do this) to determine how far away means are from one another to determine that points cluster on a plot.

5.4 Loading plots

Loading plots can be used to show how strongly each dimension influences a principal component. The angles between the variables shows how they correlate to each other. The bottom axis represents PC1, the left axis represents PC2, the top x axis shows loadings on PC1, and the right y axis is loadings on PC2.

5.5 t-SNE plot

t-SNE plots are similar to PCA plots. They show different groupings of your data points, but in t-SNE plots, the neighboring cluster is important as well. The distance between clusters or individual points represents their similarity to each other. The x- and y- axes are non-linear on t-SNE plots and these are typically only used for data exploration.
